f=AI & Agents/meta/marketplace/writing-skills/SKILL.md · tx=<!-- SELECTED: strongest real marketplace skill writing agent skills test-driven documentation (RED-GREEN-REFACTOR applied SKILL.md files): watch agent fail WITHOUT skill before trusting skill teaches right thing. trusted source family already-adopted Shared skill `verification-before-completion` (obra/superpowers). Compared against joshuadavidthomas/agent-skills skill-authoring (thinner, format-only) agentskills.io spec spec, method). COMPANION FILES COPIED (upstream, fetch deploy wanted): · tx=anthropic-best-practices.md distilled citation meta's custom skill-authoring-standards, testing-skills-with-subagents.md, persuasion-principles.md, graphviz-conventions.dot, render-graphs.js · tx=https://github.com/obra/superpowers/tree/main/skills/writing-skills BOUNDARIES: skill's conventions differ house standard (playbook §11 frontmatter, provenance rules, genericization), meta's custom `skill-authoring-standards` WINS. skill supplies testing method; house standard supplies format law. Original content follows, verbatim uncut. --> · h2:Overview=**Writing skills Test-Driven Development applied process documentation.** **Personal skills live your runtime's skills directory** see [claude-code-tools.md](../using-superpowers/references/claude-code-tools.md), [codex-tools.md](../using-superpowers/references/codex-tools.md), [copilot-tools.md](../using-superpowers/references/copilot-tools.md), [gemini-tools.md](../using-superpowers/references/gemini-tools.md) path your runtime. Codex, Copilot CLI, Gemini CLI recognize `~/.agents/skills/` cross-runtime alias. You write test cases (pressure scenarios subagents), watch them fail (baseline behavior), write skill (documentation), watch tests pass (agents comply), refactor (close loopholes). **Core principle:** you didn't watch agent fail without skill, you don't know skill teaches right thing. **REQUIRED BACKGROUND:** You understand superpowers:test-driven-development before using skill. skill defines fundamental RED-GREEN-REFACTOR cycle. skill adapts TDD documentation. **Official guidance:** Anthropic's official skill authoring best practices, see anthropic-best-practices.md. document provides additional patterns guidelines complement TDD-focused approach skill. · wh:is a Skill?=**skill** reference guide proven techniques, patterns, tools. Skills help future agents find apply effective approaches. **Skills are:** Reusable techniques, patterns, tools, reference guides **Skills NOT:** Narratives about you solved problem once · h2:TDD Mapping for Skills=\| TDD Concept \| Skill Creation \| · h2:TDD Mapping for Skills=\|-------------\|----------------\| · h2:TDD Mapping for Skills=\| **Test case** \| Pressure scenario with subagent \| · h2:TDD Mapping for Skills=\| **Production code** \| Skill document (SKILL.md) \| · h2:TDD Mapping for Skills=\| **Test fails (RED)** \| Agent violates rule without skill (baseline) \| · h2:TDD Mapping for Skills=\| **Test passes (GREEN)** \| Agent complies with skill present \| · h2:TDD Mapping for Skills=\| **Refactor** \| Close loopholes while maintaining compliance \| · h2:TDD Mapping for Skills=\| **Write test first** \| Run baseline scenario BEFORE writing skill \| · h2:TDD Mapping for Skills=\| **Watch it fail** \| Document exact rationalizations agent uses \| · h2:TDD Mapping for Skills=\| **Minimal code** \| Write skill addressing those specific violations \| · h2:TDD Mapping for Skills=\| **Watch it pass** \| Verify agent now complies \| · h2:TDD Mapping for Skills=\| **Refactor cycle** \| Find new rationalizations → plug → re-verify \| · h2:TDD Mapping for Skills=entire skill creation process follows RED-GREEN-REFACTOR. · h2:Create Skill=**Create when:** · h2:Create Skill=Technique wasn't intuitively obvious you, You'd reference again across projects, Pattern applies broadly (not project-specific), Others would benefit · h2:Create Skill=**Don't create for:** · h2:Create Skill=One-off solutions, Standard practices well-documented elsewhere, Project-specific conventions (put your instructions file), Mechanical constraints (if it's enforceable regex/validation, automate it—save documentation judgment calls) · h3:Technique=Concrete method steps follow (condition-based-waiting, root-cause-tracing) · h3:Pattern=Way thinking about problems (flatten-with-flags, test-invariants) · h3:Reference=API docs, syntax guides, tool documentation (office docs) · h2:Directory Structure=`skills/ \· skill-name/ \· SKILL.md              # Main reference (required) \· supporting-file.*     # Only if needed` · h2:Directory Structure=**Flat namespace** skills one searchable namespace **Separate files for:** **Heavy reference** (100+ lines) API docs, comprehensive syntax **Reusable tools** Scripts, utilities, templates **Keep inline:** · h2:Directory Structure=Principles and concepts, Code patterns lines), Everything else · h2:SKILL.md Structure=**Frontmatter (YAML):** · h2:SKILL.md Structure=` \· # Skill Name \·  \· ## Overview \· What is this? Core principle in 1-2 sentences.` · h2:SKILL.md Structure=Two required fields: `name` `description` (see [agentskills.io/specification](https://agentskills.io/specification) supported fields), Max 1024 characters total, `name`: Use letters, numbers, hyphens (no parentheses, special chars), `description`: Third-person, describes use (NOT what does), Start "Use when..." focus triggering conditions, Include specific symptoms, situations, contexts, **NEVER summarize skill's process workflow** (see SDO section why), Keep under 500 characters possible · h2:Skill Discovery Optimization (SDO)=**Critical discovery:** Future agents need FIND your skill · h3:1. Rich Description Field=`# ❌ BAD: Summarizes workflow - agents may follow this instead of reading skill \· description: Use when executing plans - dispatches subagent per task with code review between tasks \·  \· # ❌ BAD: Too much process detail \· description: Use for TDD - write test first, watch it fail, write minimal code, refactor` · h3:1. Rich Description Field=**Purpose:** Your agent reads description decide which skills load given task. Make answer: "Should read skill right now?" **Format:** Start "Use when..." focus triggering conditions **CRITICAL: Description Use, What Skill Does** description describe triggering conditions. summarize skill's process workflow description. **Why matters:** Testing revealed description summarizes skill's workflow, agent follow description instead reading full skill content. description saying "code review between tasks" caused agent ONE review, even though skill's flowchart clearly showed TWO reviews (spec compliance code quality). description changed "Use executing implementation plans independent tasks" (no workflow summary), agent correctly read flowchart followed two-stage review process. **The trap:** Descriptions summarize workflow create shortcut agents take. skill body becomes documentation agents skip. **Content:** · h3:1. Rich Description Field=`# ❌ BAD: Too abstract, vague, doesn't include when to use \· description: For async testing \·  \· # ❌ BAD: First person \· description: I can help you with async tests when they're flaky` · h3:1. Rich Description Field=Use concrete triggers, symptoms, situations signal skill applies, Describe *problem* (race conditions, inconsistent behavior) *language-specific symptoms* (setTimeout, sleep), Keep triggers technology-agnostic unless skill itself technology-specific, skill technology-specific, make explicit trigger, Write third person (injected system prompt), **NEVER summarize skill's process workflow** · h3:2. Keyword Coverage=Use words agent search for: · h3:2. Keyword Coverage=Error messages: "Hook timed out", "ENOTEMPTY", "race condition", Symptoms: "flaky", "hanging", "zombie", "pollution", Synonyms: "timeout/hang/freeze", "cleanup/teardown/afterEach", Tools: Actual commands, library names, file types · h3:3. Descriptive Naming=**Use active voice, verb-first:** · h3:3. Descriptive Naming=✅ `creating-skills` not `skill-creation`, ✅ `condition-based-waiting` not `async-test-helpers` · h3:4. Token Efficiency (Critical)=**Problem:** getting-started frequently-referenced skills load conversation. token counts. **Target word counts:** · h3:4. Token Efficiency (Critical)=getting-started workflows: <150 words, Frequently-loaded skills: <200 words total, skills: <500 words (still concise) · h3:4. Token Efficiency (Critical)=`# ❌ BAD: Document all flags in SKILL.md \· search-conversations supports --text, --both, --after DATE, --before DATE, --limit N \·  \· # ✅ GOOD: Reference --help \· search-conversations supports multiple modes and filters. Run --help for details.` · h3:4. Token Efficiency (Critical)=`# ❌ BAD: Repeat workflow details \· When searching, dispatch subagent with template... \· [20 lines of repeated instructions] \·  \· # ✅ GOOD: Reference other skill` · h3:4. Token Efficiency (Critical)=`# ❌ BAD: Verbose example (42 words) \· your human partner: "How did we handle authentication errors in React Router before?" \· You: I'll search past conversations for React Router authentication patterns. \· [Dispatch subagent with search query: "React Router authentication error handling 401"] \· ` · h3:4. Token Efficiency (Critical)=**Techniques:** **Move details tool help:** **Use cross-references:** **Compress examples:** **Eliminate redundancy:** · h3:4. Token Efficiency (Critical)=Don't repeat what's cross-referenced skills, Don't explain what's obvious command, Don't include multiple examples pattern · h3:4. Token Efficiency (Critical)=`wc -w skills/path/SKILL.md \· # getting-started workflows: aim for <150 each \· # Other frequently-loaded: aim for <200 total` · h3:4. Token Efficiency (Critical)=**Verification:** **Name what you core insight:** · h3:4. Token Efficiency (Critical)=✅ `condition-based-waiting` > `async-test-helpers`, ✅ `using-skills` not `skill-usage`, ✅ `flatten-with-flags` > `data-structure-refactoring`, ✅ `root-cause-tracing` > `debugging-techniques` · h3:4. Token Efficiency (Critical)=**Gerunds (-ing) work well processes:** · h3:4. Token Efficiency (Critical)=`creating-skills`, `testing-skills`, `debugging-with-logs`, Active, describes action you're taking · h3:5. Cross-Referencing Other Skills=**When writing documentation references skills:** Use skill name only, explicit requirement markers: · h3:5. Cross-Referencing Other Skills=Good: `**REQUIRED SUB-SKILL:** Use superpowers:test-driven-development`, Good: `**REQUIRED BACKGROUND:** You understand superpowers:systematic-debugging`, Bad: `See skills/testing/test-driven-development` (unclear required), Bad: `@skills/testing/test-driven-development/SKILL.md` (force-loads, burns context) · h3:5. Cross-Referencing Other Skills=**Why links:** `@` syntax force-loads files immediately, consuming 200k+ context before you need them. · h2:Flowchart Usage=`digraph when_flowchart { \· "Need to show information?" [shape=diamond]; \· "Decision where I might go wrong?" [shape=diamond]; \· "Use markdown" [shape=box]; \· "Small inline flowchart" [shape=box];` · h2:Flowchart Usage=**Use flowcharts ONLY for:** · h2:Flowchart Usage=Non-obvious decision points, Process loops you stop early, "When use decisions · h2:Flowchart Usage=**Never use flowcharts for:** · h2:Flowchart Usage=Reference material Tables, lists, Code examples Markdown blocks, Linear instructions Numbered lists, Labels without semantic meaning (step1, helper2) · h2:Flowchart Usage=`./render-graphs.js ../some-skill           # Each diagram separately \· ./render-graphs.js ../some-skill --combine # All diagrams in one SVG` · h2:Flowchart Usage=See `graphviz-conventions.dot` directory graphviz style rules. **Visualizing your human partner:** Use `render-graphs.js` directory render skill's flowcharts SVG: · h2:Code Examples=**One excellent example beats many mediocre ones** Choose relevant language: · h2:Code Examples=Testing techniques → TypeScript/JavaScript, System debugging → Shell/Python, Data processing → Python · h2:Code Examples=**Good example:** · h2:Code Examples=Complete and runnable, Well-commented explaining WHY, From real scenario, Shows pattern clearly, Ready adapt (not generic template) · h2:Code Examples=**Don't:** · h2:Code Examples=Implement in 5+ languages, Create fill-in-the-blank templates, Write contrived examples · h2:Code Examples=You're good porting one great example enough. · h3:Self-Contained Skill=`defense-in-depth/ \· SKILL.md    # Everything inline` · h3:Self-Contained Skill=When: content fits, heavy reference needed · h3:Skill with Reusable Tool=`condition-based-waiting/ \· SKILL.md    # Overview + patterns \· example.ts  # Working helpers to adapt` · h3:Skill with Reusable Tool=When: Tool reusable code, narrative · h3:Skill with Heavy Reference=`pptx/ \· SKILL.md       # Overview + workflows \· pptxgenjs.md   # 600 lines API reference \· ooxml.md       # 500 lines XML structure \· scripts/       # Executable tools` · h3:Skill with Heavy Reference=When: Reference material large inline · h2:Iron Law (Same TDD)=`NO SKILL WITHOUT A FAILING TEST FIRST` · h2:Iron Law (Same TDD)=applies NEW skills EDITS existing skills. Write skill before testing? Delete it. Start over. Edit skill without testing? violation. **No exceptions:** · h2:Iron Law (Same TDD)=Not for "simple additions", "just adding section", Not for "documentation updates", Don't keep untested changes "reference", Don't "adapt" while running tests, Delete means delete · h2:Iron Law (Same TDD)=**REQUIRED BACKGROUND:** superpowers:test-driven-development skill explains matters. principles apply documentation. · te:ing All Skill Types=Different skill types need different test approaches: · h3:Discipline-Enforcing Skills (rules/requirements)=**Examples:** TDD, verification-before-completion, designing-before-coding **Test with:** · h3:Discipline-Enforcing Skills (rules/requirements)=Academic questions: they understand rules?, Pressure scenarios: they comply under stress?, Multiple pressures combined: time sunk cost exhaustion, Identify rationalizations add explicit counters · h3:Discipline-Enforcing Skills (rules/requirements)=**Success criteria:** Agent follows rule under maximum pressure · h3:Technique Skills (how-to guides)=**Examples:** condition-based-waiting, root-cause-tracing, defensive-programming **Test with:** · h3:Technique Skills (how-to guides)=Application scenarios: they apply technique correctly?, Variation scenarios: they handle edge cases?, Missing information tests: instructions gaps? · h3:Technique Skills (how-to guides)=**Success criteria:** Agent successfully applies technique new scenario · h3:Pattern Skills (mental models)=**Examples:** reducing-complexity, information-hiding concepts **Test with:** · h3:Pattern Skills (mental models)=Recognition scenarios: they recognize pattern applies?, Application scenarios: they use mental model?, Counter-examples: they know apply? · h3:Pattern Skills (mental models)=**Success criteria:** Agent correctly identifies when/how apply pattern · h3:Reference Skills (documentation/APIs)=**Examples:** API documentation, command references, library guides **Test with:** · h3:Reference Skills (documentation/APIs)=Retrieval scenarios: they find right information?, Application scenarios: they use what they found correctly?, Gap testing: common use cases covered? · h3:Reference Skills (documentation/APIs)=**Success criteria:** Agent finds correctly applies reference information · h2:Common Rationalizations Skipping Testing=\| Excuse \| Reality \| · h2:Common Rationalizations Skipping Testing=\|--------\|---------\| · h2:Common Rationalizations Skipping Testing=\| "Skill is obviously clear" \| Clear to you ≠ clear to other agents. Test it. \| · h2:Common Rationalizations Skipping Testing=\| "It's just a reference" \| References can have gaps, unclear sections. Test retrieval. \| · h2:Common Rationalizations Skipping Testing=\| "Testing is overkill" \| Untested skills have issues. Always. 15 min testing saves hours. \| · h2:Common Rationalizations Skipping Testing=\| "I'll test if problems emerge" \| Problems = agents can't use skill. Test BEFORE deploying. \| · h2:Common Rationalizations Skipping Testing=\| "Too tedious to test" \| Testing is less tedious than debugging bad skill in production. \| · h2:Common Rationalizations Skipping Testing=\| "I'm confident it's good" \| Overconfidence guarantees issues. Test anyway. \| · h2:Common Rationalizations Skipping Testing=\| "Academic review is enough" \| Reading ≠ using. Test application scenarios. \| · h2:Common Rationalizations Skipping Testing=\| "No time to test" \| Deploying untested skill wastes more time fixing it later. \| · h2:Common Rationalizations Skipping Testing=**All mean: Test before deploying. exceptions.** · h2:Match Form Failure=Before writing guidance, classify baseline failure. form bulletproofs one failure type measurably backfires another. · h2:Match Form Failure=\| Baseline failure \| Right form \| Wrong form \| · h2:Match Form Failure=\|---\|---\|---\| · h2:Match Form Failure=\| Skips/violates a rule under pressure (knows better, does it anyway) \| Prohibition + rationalization table + red flags (see Bulletproofing below) \| Soft guidance ("prefer...", "consider...") \| · h2:Match Form Failure=\| Complies, but output has the wrong shape (bloated prompt, buried verdict, restated spec) \| Positive recipe or contract: state what the output IS — its parts, in order \| Prohibition list ("don't restate", "never narrate") \| · h2:Match Form Failure=\| Omits a required element from something they already produce \| Structural: REQUIRED field or slot in the template they fill in \| Prose reminders near the template \| · h2:Match Form Failure=\| Behavior should depend on a condition \| Conditional keyed to an observable predicate ("if the brief exists, reference it") \| Unconditional rule + exemption clauses \| · h2:Match Form Failure=**Why prohibitions backfire shaping problems:** under competing incentive ("make prompt self-contained"), agents negotiate "don't X". head-to-head wording tests dispatch-prompt guidance, prohibition arm produced clearly unwanted content recipe arm (fully separated distributions), trended worse even no-guidance control micro-test your case rather assuming, never reach prohibition default. recipe leaves nothing negotiate: output matches stated shape doesn't. **Rules whichever form you pick:** · h2:Match Form Failure=**No nuance clauses.** "Don't unless matters" reopens negotiation appending single nuance clause winning recipe degraded consistent noisy wording tests. Express real exception conditional observable predicate., **Exemption clauses don't scope.** "This limit doesn't apply code blocks" still suppresses code blocks. part output exempt, restructure rule can't reach it. · h2:Bulletproofing Skills Against Rationalization=Skills enforce discipline (like TDD) need resist rationalization. Agents smart find loopholes under pressure. **Scope:** toolkit discipline failures agent knows rule skips under pressure. wrong-shaped output omitted elements, prohibition-based bulletproofing backfires; use forms Match Form Failure instead. **Psychology note:** Understanding persuasion techniques work helps you apply them systematically. See persuasion-principles.md research foundation (Cialdini, 2021; Meincke al., 2025) authority, commitment, scarcity, social proof, unity principles. · h3:Close Every Loophole Explicitly=`Write code before test? Delete it.` · h3:Close Every Loophole Explicitly=`Write code before test? Delete it. Start over. \·  \· **No exceptions:** \· - Don't keep it as "reference" \· - Don't "adapt" it while writing tests` · h3:Close Every Loophole Explicitly=Don't state rule forbid specific workarounds: <Bad> </Bad> <Good> </Good> · h3:Address "Spirit Letter" Arguments=`**Violating the letter of the rules is violating the spirit of the rules.**` · h3:Address "Spirit Letter" Arguments=Add foundational principle early: cuts off entire class "I'm following spirit" rationalizations. · h3:Build Rationalization Table=`\| Excuse \| Reality \| \· \|--------\|---------\| \· \| "Too simple to test" \| Simple code breaks. Test takes 30 seconds. \| \· \| "I'll test after" \| Tests passing immediately prove nothing. \| \· \| "Tests after achieve same goals" \| Tests-after = "what does this do?" Tests-first = "what should this do?" \|` · h3:Build Rationalization Table=Capture rationalizations baseline testing (see Testing section below). excuse agents make goes table: · h3:Create Red Flags List=`## Red Flags - STOP and Start Over \·  \· - Code before test \· - "I already manually tested it" \· - "Tests after achieve the same purpose"` · h3:Create Red Flags List=Make easy agents self-check rationalizing: · h3:Update SDO Violation Symptoms=`description: use when implementing any feature or bugfix, before writing implementation code` · h3:Update SDO Violation Symptoms=Add description: symptoms you're ABOUT violate rule: · h2:RED-GREEN-REFACTOR for Skills=Follow the TDD cycle: · h3:RED: Write Failing Test (Baseline)=Run pressure scenario subagent WITHOUT skill. Document exact behavior: · h3:RED: Write Failing Test (Baseline)=What choices they make?, What rationalizations they use (verbatim)?, Which pressures triggered violations? · h3:RED: Write Failing Test (Baseline)="watch test fail" you see what agents naturally before writing skill. · h3:GREEN: Write Minimal Skill=Write skill addresses specific rationalizations. Don't add extra content hypothetical cases. Run scenarios skill. Agent comply. · h3:REFACTOR: Close Loopholes=Agent found new rationalization? Add explicit counter. Re-test until bulletproof. · h3:Micro-Test Wording Before Full Scenarios=Full pressure-scenario runs final gate, they slow expensive iteration. Verify wording itself first micro-tests: **One fresh-context sample call** raw API call, single-shot subagent you don't API access. System prompt realistic context guidance live (the full skill prompt template, guidance isolation); user message task tempts failure. **Always include no-guidance control.** control doesn't exhibit failure, nothing fix stop, don't author guidance. **5+ reps variant.** Single samples lie. **Manually read flagged match.** Score programmatically you like, template echoes quoted counter-examples masquerade hits; automated counts alone overstate failure success. **Variance metric.** guidance lands, reps converge shape. Five different interpretations across five reps means wording isn't binding tighten form before adding words. Micro-tests verify wording; they replace pressure scenarios discipline skills. **Testing methodology:** See [testing-skills-with-subagents.md](testing-skills-with-subagents.md) complete testing methodology: · h3:Micro-Test Wording Before Full Scenarios=write pressure scenarios, Pressure types (time, sunk cost, authority, exhaustion), Plugging holes systematically, Meta-testing techniques · h3:❌ Narrative Example="In session 2025-10-03, found empty projectDir caused..." **Why bad:** specific, reusable · h3:❌ Multi-Language Dilution=example-js.js, example-py.py, example-go.go **Why bad:** Mediocre quality, maintenance burden · h3:❌ Code in Flowcharts=`step1 [label="import fs"]; \· step2 [label="read file"];` · h3:❌ Code in Flowcharts=**Why bad:** Can't copy-paste, hard read · h3:❌ Generic Labels=helper1, helper2, step3, pattern4 **Why bad:** Labels semantic meaning · h2:STOP: Before Moving Next Skill=**After writing ANY skill, you STOP complete deployment process.** **Do NOT:** · h2:STOP: Before Moving Next Skill=Create multiple skills batch without testing, Move next skill before current one verified, Skip testing because "batching efficient" · h2:STOP: Before Moving Next Skill=**The deployment checklist below MANDATORY skill.** Deploying untested skills deploying untested code. It's violation quality standards. · h2:Skill Creation Checklist (TDD Adapted)=**IMPORTANT: Create todo checklist item below.** **RED Phase Write Failing Test:** · h2:Skill Creation Checklist (TDD Adapted)=Create pressure scenarios (3+ combined pressures discipline skills), Run scenarios WITHOUT skill document baseline behavior verbatim, Identify patterns rationalizations/failures · h2:Skill Creation Checklist (TDD Adapted)=**GREEN Phase Write Minimal Skill:** · h2:Skill Creation Checklist (TDD Adapted)=Name uses letters, numbers, hyphens (no parentheses/special chars), YAML frontmatter required `name` `description` fields (max 1024 chars; see [spec](https://agentskills.io/specification)), Description starts "Use when..." includes specific triggers/symptoms, Description written third person, Keywords throughout search (errors, symptoms, tools), Clear overview core principle, Address specific baseline failures identified RED, Guidance form matches failure type (see Match Form Failure), behavior-shaping guidance: wording micro-tested against no-guidance control (5+ reps, flagged match read manually) N/A pure reference skills, Code inline link separate file, One excellent example (not multi-language), Run scenarios skill verify agents comply · h2:Skill Creation Checklist (TDD Adapted)=**REFACTOR Phase Close Loopholes:** · h2:Skill Creation Checklist (TDD Adapted)=Identify NEW rationalizations testing, Add explicit counters (if discipline skill), Build rationalization table test iterations, Create red flags list, Re-test until bulletproof · h2:Skill Creation Checklist (TDD Adapted)=**Quality Checks:** · h2:Skill Creation Checklist (TDD Adapted)=Small flowchart decision non-obvious, Quick reference table, Common mistakes section, narrative storytelling, Supporting files tools heavy reference · h2:Skill Creation Checklist (TDD Adapted)=**Deployment:** · h2:Skill Creation Checklist (TDD Adapted)=Commit skill git push your fork (if configured), Consider contributing back (if broadly useful) · h2:Discovery Workflow=future agents find your skill: **Encounters problem** ("tests flaky") **Searches skills** (greps descriptions, browses categories) **Finds SKILL** (description matches) **Scans overview** (is relevant?) **Reads patterns** (quick reference table) **Loads example** (only implementing) **Optimize flow** put searchable terms early often. · h2:The Bottom Line=**Creating skills TDD process documentation.** Iron Law: skill without failing test first. cycle: RED (baseline) GREEN (write skill) REFACTOR (close loopholes). benefits: Better quality, fewer surprises, bulletproof results. you follow TDD code, follow skills. It's discipline applied documentation.